oldsman", "roles_in_work": [{"id": 907646, "title": "Lost in space", "work_id": 88122, "role": "co-producer", "role_id": 915, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2184503, "title": "Deep blue sea", "work_id": 95045, "role": "co-producer", "role_id": 915, "is_primary": true}], "also_known_as": "", "date_of_birth": "1962-07-07", "date_of_death": "", "genders": [{"id": 9, "name": "Male", "slug": "male"}], "languages": [{"id": 1, "name": "English", "slug": "english"}], "places_of_operation": [{"id": 1, "name": "United States of America", "slug": "united-states-of-america"}], "biography": "Akiva Goldsman (born July 7, 1962) is an American filmmaker. He is known for making motion pictures and adaptations of popular novels.Goldsman's filmography as a screenwriter includes The Client; Batman Forever and its sequel Batman & Robin; I, Robot; I Am Legend; Cinderella Man, and numerous rewrites that are both credited and uncredited. He also wrote more than a dozen episodes for the science fiction television series Fringe.\nIn 2002, Goldsman received the Oscar for Best Adapted Screenplay and the Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay for the 2001 film A Beautiful Mind, which also won the Academy Award for Best Picture. In 2006, Goldsman re-teamed with A Beautiful Mind director Ron Howard to adapt Dan Brown's novel The Da Vinci Code for Howard's film. He also wrote the screenplay for its 2009 sequel Angels & Demons.\nGoldsman is also known for co-developing the DC Comics TV series Titans and the Paramount Plus series Star Trek: Picard, a sequel to Star Trek: The Next Generation and Star Trek: Nemesis. He is also the co-creator of Star Trek: Strange New Worlds, a prequel to Star Trek: The Original Series.", "biography_author": "Wikidata", "date_of_biography": "2023-08-01T13:54:31.251652+10:00", "external_links": [{"id": 1564, "uri": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akiva_Goldsman"}], "uuid": "46247ec0-c0f9-4a1c-bcf5-a2d0210d3d95", "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identi